title: Adjustable Electric Motor Mount for RC Plane (NTM 42-58)

description.text:
This is an electric motor mount designed for my Phoenix Edge 540 (55.5" wingspan). It is made to work with any of the cheap 42mm NTM prop-drive motors from Hobbyking. I made it to be roughly the right length so that the prop on the electric motor when mounted sits at the same length from the firewall as the prop did when on the original nitro motor.

Motor mount holes are roughly 48x48mm (designed to be used with the aluminum plate that is included in the NTM prop drive accessory kit also from Hobbyking). Firewall mounting holes are approximately 45x45mm. All holes are 4mm so should work fine with 4-40 hardware or 3-4mm hardware.

The mount is likely extremely over-built but I went for safety and durability! On 6s (22.2v) this motor is going to pull like crazy!

Motor:
http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__70917__NTM_Prop_Drive_Series_42_58_500kv_1300w_AR_Warehouse_.html
Motor accessory kit: http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__70914__NTM_Prop_Drive_42_Series_Accessory_Pack_AR_Warehouse_.html

UPDATE: I have now uploaded an updated version of the mount that features adjustable mounting positions.

Printer:

Turnigy Fabrikator

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I would lay the mount on its side and print using lined supports for the middle, circular section. I would recommend 100% infill for maximum strength (remember this is essentially holding all of the weight of the plane plus any other forces the plane may experience). I am printing the piece in ABS, but PLA would probably be fine, too.

NOTE: I would recommend doing several bench test to ensure that this mount is strong enough! It must support the entire weight of the loaded plane and more!

I just rounded out the back of the original thing and scaled it up 33%, so as to use it as a costume prop.

I originally remixed this for an Alice in Wonderland themed Mad Hatter's Tea Party. I can imagine using it for various other costumes.

Colors

I found it impossible on my printer to make the detailed pieces from the original in order to have a raw plastic multi-colored pocketwatch (though the glow-in-the-dark hands and numbers on one of the photos on the original reallllly appealed to me), so I stuck with the single print version in white.

Then I took a hobby knife and sandpaper to my white plastic pocketwatch in order to smooth it out, and sprayed it with gold. Then I had a 13 year old with patience and a small paintbrush paint the face of it.

Then, in order to preserve the paint, I sprayed a coat of clear, gloss enamel on it, which unfortunately made the gold less shiny. :-( Oh well, you live you learn.

Chain

One could use a real chain to make it look more realistic.

I just used some shiny gold elastic and a safety pin.

I may have once received the elastic wrapped around a present. I'm a pack rat.

SketchUp

I used Sketchup to add the rounded off back, and made very few other changes.

The STL mesh was pretty well mangled by being imported into SketchUp, though.

Netfabb Basic

I did not have the patience to manually clean up this well detailed model inside of SketchUp, so instead of insisting on creating a fully solid model, as is my usual goal, I relied on Netfabb's Basic Repair tool to repair the STL after exporting it from SketchUp.

I'm Building a Custom CoreXY printer using V-Slot.

The V-Slot is reasonably priced however the Accessories for it are quite expensive and Will ADD UP! So I am going to design A lot of parts for ABS Printing.

This is an in Progress Thing!

So far it's just a couple of Parts to Join the V-Slot together, The Cube part Has 3x 5mm holes for joining 3 pieces of V-Slot at the top (when you TAP the V-SLot) thus enabling you to make a Square or rectangular Frame, the 3 larger holes are so you can get the Bolt in the cube.

V2 of cube added: Rounded corners, internal countersink for CapHead Bolts

Corner Piece is pretty Self explanatory, M5 10mm Dome head Screws work best.

I've just came across this http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:105900 Which is the open builds versions, I did not copy these designs, however my design and their designs are very similar.

03-07-2016: Added a Nema17 Mount to attach the motor to the vslot, I still have to make a second mount that is higher than the first as I plan to use a "over and under" drive belts rather than the traditional crossed belts. this mount uses 3x M5 Cap head bolts to secure to the vslot and 4x M3 cap head's to attach the nema17

05-7-2016: Added 2nd Nema17 Mount this one is taller to raise the Gear Pulley above the first mount allowing an over under belt system, I may change this model.

06-7-2016: Added V3 of the cube, the previous 2 versions will need to be drilled to allow for a Cap Head bolt, V2 will work ok for button head bolts. V3 is optimised for button head bolts, cap head bolts are a poor choice they would require making the supporting plastic a lot thiner.

09-7-2016: changed the Nema17 Mounts from cap head bolts to button head bolts. I'm using M5 10mm Button head bolts for everything on this build now.

24-7-2016: Added RodFixing, it allows you to fit 10mm Smoth rod to the V-Slot / T-slot Extrusions.

21-11-2016 Added Custom Y-Plates the Y plate is loosely based on the Openbuilds Mini V gantry plate however the hole spacings are designed to do away with the Eccentric spacers, using mini wheels which you can get from your usual Chinese distributors, one orientation will give you a tighter fit than the other orientation (that's what the two squares are for on the top)

20-11-2016 Improved the X and Y gantry Plates, they work much better now
no adjustment or messing about is needed for use with the mini gantry wheels, just
4x m5 25mm bolts
4x m5 standard hex nuts
4x m5 washers
4x mini V wheels
8x m5 lock nuts

it is important to use lock nuts! as the inner diameter of the locking part of the nut is the perfect size to not lock up the mini wheels! put one either end of the wheel the locking part towards the wheel! (so the last lock nut is backwards)

Drill out the 4 holes with a 5mm drill bit to make sure the bolts fit through without being held by the plastic, the nuts on the rear are used to hold the bold straight and in place, if you screw the bolt through the plastic (which is very easy) it is very probable that it will be at a slight angle! (you don't want that) https://youtu.be/fFbzME6J3Ao

description.text:
Attached is a photo of the device that I constructed out of PVC that holds the FilaStruder at a 45 degree angle. At least for me, it's resulted in much more consistent extrusion when demoing the unit.  
This was a quick hack that I came up with when showing the Filastruder at the Orlando Mini Maker Faire, but it turned out so nicely I'm sharing it.

The support is made from 1/2" diameter PVC. I bought one tube, and chopped it up with an oscillating tool.
  • 3 short cross-pieces (about 6 inches) that run across the width of the Filastruder
  • 2 very short pieces (about 2 inches) at the front of the filastruder
  • 4 long pieces (about a foot) that run along the sides and up the back. The exact length will depend on the length of your Filastruder.
  • 6 T-joints
  • 2 L-joints (or use T-joints, if that's what you have)
    • To assemble it, I started with the front. I started with the very short pieces, each with an L-joint and a T-joint, so the open ends face the same way. I put two short pieces into one, so it looks like an F, then pushed the other very short piece (and joints) so that it forms a rectangle. This is what will fit under the front of the Filastruder. Then I put two long pieces into the open end of the T-joints, so they run to the back of the Filastruder. Then I put two T-joints onto the ends, with the end of the T pointing up. Then I assembled the two other long pieces, the short piece, and the two T-joints into a very tall H. The back of the Filastruder will rest on the cross-bar of the H. I finished the frame by pushing the bottom of the H into T-joints. Then wiggle the structure around so that it lies square on the table, and hammer the assembly together so that the joints lock in place. Put a tight loop of blue painter's tape around the two short pieces at the front. Then put the Filastruder's front on the tape, between the two front cross pieces. The weight of the Filastruder should be on the tape between the front cross-pieces, holding the front firmly on the table. I had to move the fan up a little bit so that it cleared the front cross-piece. Then adjust the arms so that the filament comes straight out the nozzle and down. From there, operate the Filastruder normally. To pack the support for moving, pull the "H" at the back from the T-joints at the bottom. Then you can pack the two "U" shapes around the Filastruder.

description.text:
So I closed up 4 sides of my Lulzbot Mini and restricted the top to a 1.75" slot for access to the filament clamp on the extruder and also obviously to allow an unrestricted path for the filament to the extruder. This modification allows you to close that gap down greatly to retain some heat losses and also to minimize air flow out and hence general air in leakage. I might fine tune this some more to see if I can reduce to two main parts instead of three. The little "locating pins" x4 used on the right hand side allow you to accurately position the RHS to the middle and I then glued together with acetone. I may actually replace these with pins integral to one or other part if I stay with 3 parts as these pins are delicate at the collet end. The "stiff clamps" x4 between the middle and LHS parts allow you to replace filaments easily - they are a little hard to put on but they do hold the parts together really firmly. When you print them you may need to give a little twist to the arms to break the two pins away from each other. You can use them also on the RHS also instead of the locating pins.
I haven't used the tabs on this version but they can be glued one on each side to the underside of the RHS and LHS parts to stop any drift left or right. As always spin part on slicing SW to get optimum print.

This is a model of "the Brain" from the famous comic "Pinky & the Brain". title: Nylon Filament Print, Storage & Drying Container

description.text:
After reading the importance of keeping nylon as dry as possible to reach good results and the speed with which Nylon absorbs humidity from the air (we usually have humidity of 80+ over here), I build the pictured container in order to keep the nylon as dry as possible during use and storage.  
See the instructions for the material required to complete this project.

You will need:
  • Container seal (printable, part of this thing)
  • Silicate container top and bottom (printable, part of this thing)
  • Spool rack (download here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:74278)
  • Plastic Container (dimensions of the one I used: 20cm wide x 13cm deep x 16cm tall)
  • Desiccant dehumidifiers (make sure the pellets are not to small as they will fall through the holes in the top container otherwise) - keep out of the reach of children.
    • Print the spool rack, seal (the top cap has an inbuild support below the pins, which you need to remove once printed), top and bottom of the silicate container. Assemble the rack and filament spool and place it inside the container (see picture) and secure with double sided tape if necessary. Place the lid on top and make a hole (around 8mm diameter) so that the filament can be pulled upwards through the lid easily. Install the plug in the hole and (if necessary) open the hole inside the cap with a drill so the filament can pass through but still has a tight fit. This will allow you to hold the filament in place when you close the cap so that you can retrieve it easily for the next print without opening the lid of the box - if it slides out, simply bend the last 1mm of the filament once it is through the hole. (I will try and incorporate some kind of clamp mechanism with the next release to improve the seal even more). Place the top silicate case on top of the bottom and fill the top with silicate. I use double sided tape to stick it to the bottom of the container. In order to print, loosen the cap and pull the filament into your printer (the seal hole is the same size as the Replicator2/2x bowden tubing so you could extend it all the way from the extruder down to the case for an even better airseal. Do let me know if this worked for you in the comments section.

The design may look a bit weird because the head is missing but this is a boxing/punching puppet. Basically, it is a torso with two articulated arms. The arms can be moved by pulling a lever from the back.

The model was designed in Solvespace and exported to STL for 3d-printing.

A few things need a bit of manual adjustment: the forearms were supposed to slip inside a hole in the hands but tolerances are not adjusted properly and it won't fit without filing.

I'll possibly polish this design and reupload but I thought I'd share it.

The joints between the pieces require some form of M3 bolt+nut. Alternatively, in my build I made a little rivet using the little cylinder of a ferrule.

title: Corner Brace or Cover for 1x2 frame

description.text:
I was working on a piece of art and built a frame for the piece out of 1x2s. I didn't like how the corners turned out and I also wanted to make the piece more cohesive looking. So, I modeled and printed these corner covers or braces. This is made to fit on the mitered corner of a 1x2 frame when the wood is standing on its short end (0.75") and the longer end (1.5") is the thickness of the frame.
I print four of these for each piece I need them for. I like to use glue to adhere them to the piece (E6000 works great), and the sides are thin enough to put one small nail (with a head on it) through the side.
These SHOULD NOT be used as structural support for the frame, it is purely decorative.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Notes:

I use a Zebra plate and these corners typically peel of the raft when I am trying to remove them from the plate. It has left the raft behind, and I just scrape it off to clean up.
As I said before, I like to use E6000 glue (you can get it at any craft store or even Walmart) on one side and then use a small nail (with a head) through the other to ensure it stays in place.
I used trial and error with various 2D shapes in my CAD software and made the 3D model to print.

description.text:
This is a camera body cover for a Nikon F Mount Camera

The camera body cover can be used in two ways:

Option 1) as a simple camera body cover to prevent dust from collecting on your camera mirror or lens.

Option 2) as a pin-hole camera.
The pin-hole camera option is based on this tutorial: http://www.howtogeek.com/161794/how-to-take-pinhole-photos-with-a-digital-camera/

I didn't want to damage my original camera body cover and having a 3D printer allows me to create my own!

In order to make this part you will need to download and include the library: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1092611

This camera body cover is fully customizable so this can be used with other cameras. You will simply need to modify the model dimensions to fit your camera model.

description.header: Reusable mold to make a silicone cover for the E3D v6 hotend
description.text:
Covering the heater block will make the heater cartridge work better and improve the ability to hold temperature. Also, it will allow stronger airflows when using layer cooling fans.
 

  • Remember to run a PID auto-tune after installing this silicone cover.
Notes:

  • I've used Permatex Ultra Copper RTV because that's what I had at the moment. But using two-component high temperature silicone will be much easier to cast and with better looking results.
    FYI Permatex U.C. RTV temperature resistance is up to 316ºc, intermittent up to 371ºc. So it's great if you want to use it.

  • It's meant to be used with the "Modular Screw-on M3 Stud Thermistor" by rp_one_labs . I bought mine from here: ebay link

Please share your makes.
 
Enjoy and happy casting.
Martin

Recommended Settings:
  • Layer height: 0.20mm or less.
  • Infill: 30% works fine

  • No supports.

  • Print the parts in ABS and give them an acetone bath. Besides making a smoother surface, it will eliminate the cavities between layers and make a painless extraction.

  • Use a mold release agent for an easier extraction.

I designed this system to provide a flexible way to mount holders etc. to the printer. The rail is in 2 pieces with a long tang to connect them. Pressure works for me but you could acetone weld them into a single piece also (assuming ABS). The rail is meant to mount on the mid height screws on the sides of the printer. Get some M4 25mm screws to replace the ones in the box to mount the rails. The generic bracket and locking bar should make adding other hanging items easier. I have also included some that I have made for my purposes - a hook, a holder for a print removal spatula (the one that is popular on Amazon), and 2 size tool boxes that I use for tweezers and a box cutter knife. It should be straightforward to design other hangers and I'll add any that I design for my system.

Added a hinged trashbin meant to sit under the tray. Handy for all those bits of waste plastic that accumulate near the printer. Use a straightened thin paper clip for the hinge pin.

Added a set of "arm" parts that allow a movable mount. The hook, link, and vertical connector provide a very flexible positioning system in the horizontal plane. Multiple link parts can be used for more reach or flex. The mount parts are examples of how one can connect the target of the movable mount to the arm. In my case I mounted the case for a Pi that runs OctoPrint at the end of a hook, link, link, vertical, longmount sequence. Note that the mount parts and the vertical have matching toothed posts to provide stability in the angle of vertical positioning. Rotate as desired and then press to engage the teeth. You could certainly remix these parts to get the sort of mount/flex you want for a different application.

Added a better trash bin. After using the old one for 4+ months I decided I wanted one that was easier to remove and empty and that didn't have the lid. So there is a second bin with a hanger for the rail and the press clips to lock the hanger to the rail. The bin just lifts off to empty.

Added a slightly longer rail that fits Qidi printers.

Notes:

I printed these in ABS with supports as appropriate. I suggest printing the rails with their outer side down (no supports) and hangers with the hanger part vertical. This gives, in ABS, the right clearances. If you print in another material or in a different orientation you may need to adjust clearances to get press fit of the locking bar and clean hanging of the hangers on the rails.

More recently I printed the new trash bin in PETG. Worked fine.
